  "success": true,
  "output": "This is a pure Python job-scraper (fetchers → filter → dedup store → notify), not a React app — I'll skip the re-render section and focus on the Python-applicable categories. Here's what I found, ranked by impact:\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nEvery pipeline run does **one SELECT per job** in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n```\n\nWith `sources.yaml` now covering Microsoft/Netflix/Amazon/Apple/Google (thousands of roles per run), this is thousands of round-trips to SQLite in a loop instead of one query. Batch it:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    # SQLite caps bound params (~32k default); chunk defensively\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in cur.execute(q, chunk))\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nThis turns O(n) round-trips into O(n/900) — the single biggest win in the codebase.\n\n## 2. Redundant regex recompilation — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`_compile()` rebuilds every include/exclude pattern **for every job**, inside `match()`, which `filter_jobs()` calls once per job:\n\n```python\ndef _compile(words): return [re.compile(...) for w in words if w]  # called per-job!\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled here\n```\n\nFor N jobs and K keywords, that's N×K regex compilations of the *same* patterns. Compile once outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):   # no _compile() call\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n(`match()`'s type hints change from `list[str]` to `list[re.Pattern]` for `include`/`exclude`.)\n\n## 3. Blocking synchronous I/O inside the async pipeline — `notify.py` + `pipeline.py:44`\n\n`pipeline.run()` is `async def`, but `dispatch(new, changed)` calls `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` (sync `httpx.post`) and `notify_email` (sync `smtplib`). These block the event loop thread during network calls instead of running concurrently with anything else awaiting on it. Today it's the last step so it \"works,\" but it means notifications serialize (Slack waits on webhook waits on SMTP waits on Twilio) when they could run concurrently, and it'll bite the moment anything else needs the loop. Minimal fix — run the blocking dispatch off-thread and fan the notifiers out concurrently:\n\n```python\n# pipeline.py\nawait asyncio.to_thread(dispatch, new, changed)\n```\n\nOr better, make notifiers concurrent since they're independent I/O:\n```python\n# notify.py\nasync def dispatch(new, changed) -> None:\n    async def run(fn):\n        try:\n            await asyncio.to_thread(fn, new, changed)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n    await asyncio.gather(*(run(fn) for fn in NOTIFIERS))\n```\n\n## 4. Missing index for a query that's already used — `store.py:127-135` (`added_since`)\n\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\n```\nThis is the hot query behind every `agent.py db-new` scan, and there's no index on `first_seen` — only `idx_jobs_company` exists (line 27). SQLite will full-scan `jobs` and sort in memory every call. Add:\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n(add to `_SCHEMA` in store.py, next to the existing `idx_jobs_company` line).\n\n## 5. Minor: repeated hashing/parsing on the same `Job`\n\n- `Job.content_hash` (models.py:66-69) is a plain `@property` — sha256 over the same four fields — recomputed every access. In `Store.diff`, it's read once for comparison and again inside `to_row()` (via `_insert`/`_update`). Cheap per-call, but with the N+1 fix above you're now hashing on every job every run; if you want to avoid two hashes per changed/inserted job, compute `to_row()` once and read `row[\"content_hash\"]` for the comparison instead of calling `job.content_hash` separately.\n- `Job.posted_dt` (models.py:60-63) re-parses `posted_at` every access; it's called both in `filters.match()` and again in `agent.py cmd_db_new` for the same rows. Not worth `functools.cached_property` given `slots=True` complicates it, but if profiling ever shows this hot, switch `posted_at`/`posted_dt` handling to parse once at `Job` construction time in the fetchers rather than lazily per read.\n\nNo memory leaks stood out — `httpx.AsyncClient` is properly closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally`, and `Store` is used via context manager everywhere it matters. The pagination loops in `fetchers.py` (Apple/Google/Workday/etc.) all have explicit `max_pages` caps, so they won't runaway.\n\n**Priority to fix**: #1 (N+1) and #4 (missing index) matter most since `jobs.db` only grows over time and every run pays the cost; #2 is a quick, safe win; #3 is worth doing before you add more notifiers or run this pipeline anywhere latency-sensitive.\n",
